### ✅ Recomposition Scope — Pass Only Used Fields to Leaf Composables

Every parameter a composable reads is a **recomposition dependency**. If a card receives a full `MyFriendUI` object but only displays `name` and `imageUrl`, it will still recompose when `pokemonCards` changes — even though it never touched that field.

**Rule:** Leaf composables (cards, list items) must receive only the fields they actually display. Pass individual primitives/Strings, not the whole model object.

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — card receives MyFriendUI but only uses id, name, imageUrl.
//         If pokemonCards or description changes, the card recomposes for nothing.
@Composable
fun MyFriendCard(friend: MyFriendUI, onFriendPressed: () -> Unit) {
    Text(friend.name)    // uses name
    AsyncImage(friend.imageUrl)  // uses imageUrl
    // friend.pokemonCards and friend.description are never read — but still a dependency
}

// ✅ GOOD — card declares exactly what it needs.
@Composable
fun MyFriendCard(
    id: String,
    name: String,
    imageUrl: String,
    onFriendPressed: () -> Unit,
    onUnsubscribePressed: () -> Unit
) { ... }
```

**At the call site (inside a LazyColumn/LazyGrid item lambda):**

```kotlin
items(items = friends, key = { it.id }) { friend ->
    // Stable lambdas — recreated only if friend.id or the parent callback changes
    val onFriendPressed = remember(friend.id, onFriendClicked) { { onFriendClicked(friend.id) } }
    val onUnsubscribe = remember(friend.id, onUnsubscribeFriend) { { onUnsubscribeFriend(friend.id) } }
    MyFriendCard(
        id = friend.id,
        name = friend.name,
        imageUrl = friend.imageUrl,
        onFriendPressed = onFriendPressed,
        onUnsubscribePressed = onUnsubscribe
    )
}
```

The `remember(item.id, callback) { { callback(item.id) } }` pattern inside a lazy item is valid: each item has its own composition scope, so `remember` works per-item. The lambda is only recreated when `item.id` or `callback` changes identity.

