### ✅ Wrap Derived Values in remember()

If a composable computes a value from a **parameter** inline (e.g. `sumOf`, `filter`, `count`), that computation runs on **every recomposition** — even when the input hasn't changed.

Use `remember(param) { ... }` to run the computation only when the input changes:

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — sumOf runs on every recomposition
@Composable
fun MyDescription(pokemonCards: PersistentList<MyFriendPokemonCardUI>) {
    val totalVotes = pokemonCards.sumOf { it.totalVotes }  // recomputed every time
    Text("Total votes: $totalVotes")
}

// ✅ GOOD — sumOf runs only when pokemonCards changes
@Composable
fun MyContent(friend: MyFriendUI) {
    val totalVotes = remember(friend.pokemonCards) { friend.pokemonCards.sumOf { it.totalVotes } }
    MyDescription(totalVotes)
}

// ✅ Then the child composable takes the already-computed scalar
@Composable
fun MyDescription(totalVotes: Int) {
    Text("Total votes: $totalVotes")
}
```

Note: `derivedStateOf` is for **`MutableState` inputs**. For plain composable parameters, use `remember(key) { }`.

---

### ❌ Never Nest a Lazy Layout Inside a Scrollable Container

Placing a `LazyColumn`, `LazyVerticalGrid`, etc. inside a `Column + verticalScroll` gives the lazy layout **infinite height**. Compose is forced to lay out all items at once — defeating the entire purpose of a lazy layout.

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — LazyVerticalGrid has infinite height, all items are composed at once
Column(modifier = Modifier.verticalScroll(rememberScrollState())) {
    HeaderSection()
    LazyVerticalGrid(...) {
        items(cards) { card -> CardItem(card) }
    }
}

// ✅ GOOD — LazyVerticalGrid is the root scroller; header is a full-span item
LazyVerticalGrid(columns = GridCells.Adaptive(minSize = cellSize)) {
    item(key = "header", span = { GridItemSpan(maxLineSpan) }) {
        HeaderSection()
    }
    items(cards, key = { it.id }) { card ->
        CardItem(card)
    }
}
```

`GridItemSpan(maxLineSpan)` makes an item span **all columns** — behaving like a full-width row inside the grid. `maxLineSpan` resolves to the actual column count at runtime.

---

### ✅ Use LazyGridScope Extension Functions for Complex Grids

When a `LazyVerticalGrid` contains multiple sections (header, descriptions, separator, grid cells, empty state), extract **private `LazyGridScope` extension functions**. This keeps the main composable readable and hides the `GridItemSpan` boilerplate.

```kotlin
@Composable
fun FriendDetailContent(friend: MyFriendUI, onUnsubscribePressed: () -> Unit) {
    val totalVotes = remember(friend.pokemonCards) { friend.pokemonCards.sumOf { it.totalVotes } }

    LazyVerticalGrid(columns = GridCells.Adaptive(minSize = dimens.minGridUserCellSize)) {
        friendHeader(friend.imageUrl, friend.name, onUnsubscribePressed)
        friendDescriptions(friend.description, totalVotes)
        if (friend.pokemonCards.isEmpty()) {
            friendEmptyState(friend.name)
        } else {
            friendCardsSeparator()
            friendCards(friend.pokemonCards)
        }
    }
}

// Each section is a private LazyGridScope extension — named, keyed, and self-contained
private fun LazyGridScope.friendHeader(imageUrl: String, name: String, onUnsubscribe: () -> Unit) {
    item(key = "header", span = { GridItemSpan(maxLineSpan) }) {
        FriendDetailHeader(imageUrl, name, onUnsubscribe)
    }
}

private fun LazyGridScope.friendCards(cards: PersistentList<MyFriendPokemonCardUI>) {
    items(items = cards, key = { it.id }) { card ->
        CardThumbnail(card.imageUrl, card.name)
    }
}
// ... other sections follow the same pattern
```

**Rules for `LazyGridScope` extension functions:**
- Always `private`
- Always provide a string `key` on every `item { }` block
- Composable content (e.g. `stringResource`, theme values) goes inside the `item { }` lambda — not in the extension function itself
- Keep each function focused on one visual section

