### ✅ Annotate UI Models with @Immutable or @Stable

Without annotations, the Compose compiler treats `sealed class`, `data class`, and enums as **unstable** by default — it recomposes defensively even when nothing changed.

**Rules:**
- `@Immutable` — all `val` fields are primitives, `String`, `enum`, `@Immutable` types, or `PersistentList`. Promise: the object will never change after construction.
- `@Stable` — use when a field contains a type that has correct `equals()` but is not annotated (e.g. `android.net.Uri`). Promise: equals() is reliable.

```kotlin
// ✅ All fields are stable — use @Immutable
@Immutable
data class MyFriendPokemonCardUI(
    val id: String,
    val name: String,
    val totalVotes: Int
)

// ✅ PersistentList fields are fine — use @Immutable
@Immutable
data class MyFriendUI(
    val id: String,
    val name: String,
    val pokemonCards: PersistentList<MyFriendPokemonCardUI>
)

// ✅ Contains Uri (no @Immutable annotation in framework) — use @Stable
@Stable
data class MyProfilePokemonCardUI(
    val id: String,
    val name: String,
    val imageUri: Uri,  // Uri has correct equals() but is not @Immutable
    val totalVotes: Int
)

// ✅ Sealed UiState class — always annotate
@Immutable
sealed class MyFeatureUiState {
    data object Loading : MyFeatureUiState()
    data class Data(val items: PersistentList<ItemUI>) : MyFeatureUiState()
    data object EmptyResult : MyFeatureUiState()
}

// ❌ BAD — no annotation, Compose treats as unstable, no skipping
sealed class MyFeatureUiState { ... }
data class ItemUI(val name: String) // Compose cannot infer stability
```

### ✅ Always Use PersistentList for Collection Fields in UI Models

Plain `List<T>` is treated as **unstable** by the Compose compiler because `MutableList` implements it. `PersistentList` from `kotlinx-collections-immutable` is annotated `@Immutable` and is always safe.

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD — PersistentList is @Immutable
@Immutable
data class SearchFriendUI(
    val id: String,
    val pokemonCards: PersistentList<SearchFriendPokemonCardUI>
)

// ❌ BAD — List<T> is treated as unstable
data class SearchFriendUI(
    val id: String,
    val pokemonCards: List<SearchFriendPokemonCardUI>
)
```

### ✅ Wrap Navigation Lambdas in remember() — Tier 2 screens only

Inline lambdas that capture `LocalContext.current` or `viewModel` create a **new instance on every recomposition**. Child composables that receive them can never skip recomposition.

This optimization only pays off when the receiving composable contains a **LazyList, LazyGrid, or animated content**. On simple screens (forms, camera flows), the overhead of recomposition is negligible and adding `remember` wrappers adds complexity without visible benefit.

```kotlin
val context = LocalContext.current

// ✅ Apply on screens with LazyList / LazyGrid / animations
val onSearchFriendsPressed = remember(viewModel, context) {
    { viewModel.navigateToSearchFriend(context) }
}
val onUnsubscribePressed = remember(viewModel) { viewModel::unsubscribeFriend }

// ✅ Fine as-is on simple screens (forms, camera, static content)
onSavePressed = { viewModel.save() }
```

**When to key on what:**
- Captures only `viewModel` → `remember(viewModel) { ... }`
- Captures `viewModel` + `context` → `remember(viewModel, context) { ... }`
- Pure method reference → `remember(viewModel) { viewModel::method }`

### ✅ Use rememberUpdatedState for LaunchedEffect Callbacks

`LaunchedEffect(Unit)` starts once and never restarts. If it calls a lambda parameter (`onBackPressed`, `onSuccess`), it will hold a **stale reference** if the parent ever provides a new lambda.

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD — always calls the latest version of the callback
val currentOnBackPressed by rememberUpdatedState(onBackPressed)
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    viewModel.unsubscribed.collectLatest {
        currentOnBackPressed()
    }
}

// ❌ BAD — onBackPressed may be stale if the parent recomposed with a new lambda
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    viewModel.unsubscribed.collectLatest {
        onBackPressed()  // potentially stale reference
    }
}
```

Apply `rememberUpdatedState` to **any lambda parameter** consumed inside a `LaunchedEffect(Unit)` or `LaunchedEffect(someStableKey)`.

