## State Collection Best Practices

### ✅ Always use collectAsStateWithLifecycle() for StateFlow
`collectAsStateWithLifecycle()` automatically pauses collection when the app goes to background (lifecycle < STARTED) and resumes when it comes back. This prevents unnecessary work and resource leaks.
```kotlin
import androidx.lifecycle.compose.collectAsStateWithLifecycle

// ✅ GOOD — stops collecting in background
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()

// ❌ BAD — keeps collecting even when app is in background
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsState()
```

Required dependency in each feature module's `build.gradle.kts`:
```kotlin
implementation(libs.androidx.lifecycle.runtime.compose)
```

### ✅ Collect SharedFlow with observeWithLifecycle()

Use the `observeWithLifecycle()` extension from `coreui` to collect any `SharedFlow` in a Screen. It wraps `flowWithLifecycle` with the correct `LaunchedEffect` keys so collection is paused when the lifecycle drops below `STARTED` (app backgrounded).

```kotlin
import com.shodo.android.coreui.extensions.observeWithLifecycle

// Simple error flow — lifecycleOwner defaults to LocalLifecycleOwner.current
viewModel.error.observeWithLifecycle { error ->
    snackbarHostState.showSnackbar(error.message.toString())
}

// Pass an explicit lifecycleOwner when the Screen already has one as a parameter
viewModel.error.observeWithLifecycle(lifecycleOwner) { error ->
    snackbarHostState.showSnackbar(error.message.toString())
}

// Navigation/one-shot flow — combine with rememberUpdatedState when the callback
// may change identity across recompositions
val currentOnBackPressed by rememberUpdatedState(onBackPressed)
viewModel.unsubscribed.observeWithLifecycle(lifecycleOwner) {
    currentOnBackPressed()
}
```

**How it works:** `observeWithLifecycle` is defined in `coreui/extensions/FlowExtensions.kt`:
```kotlin
@Composable
fun <T> Flow<T>.observeWithLifecycle(
    lifecycleOwner: LifecycleOwner = LocalLifecycleOwner.current,
    minActiveState: Lifecycle.State = Lifecycle.State.STARTED,
    action: suspend (T) -> Unit
) {
    LaunchedEffect(this, lifecycleOwner) {
        flowWithLifecycle(lifecycleOwner.lifecycle, minActiveState).collect(action)
    }
}
```

**Important:** `SharedFlow` has no replay (replay = 0 by default). Events emitted while the lifecycle is below `STARTED` are lost. This is intentional and acceptable for:
- **Error flows** — stale error snackbars should not pop up when returning from background.
- **Navigation/one-shot flows** — these are immediate responses to user actions; they won't be emitted while backgrounded in normal usage.

**Never do this** — the inner `launch` escapes composable scope and creates an orphan coroutine:
```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — orphan coroutine, wrong key, no lifecycle awareness
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    lifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch {
        flowWithLifecycle(...).collect(action)
    }
}
```

### ❌ Don't collect in top-level composables repeatedly
```kotlin
// BAD - collects multiple times
val item by viewModel.item.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
val items by viewModel.items.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
val loading by viewModel.loading.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()

// GOOD - single sealed state
val uiState by viewModel.uiState.collectAsStateWithLifecycle()
```

